    {
        "content": "<p>Hello, I'm doing some Linear Algebra work right now. I have two matrices X1 and X2 and I would like to get the column span of them as if they were concatenated together. I found <code>submodule.span</code>, but I'm struggling to turn both of the matrices into a set of vectors. How could I do that? Am I even going the right way? Thanks in advance! :)</p>\n<p>So this is what I would like to do:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">variables</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"n\">p₁</span> <span class=\"n\">p₂</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">X₁</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">matrix</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">fin</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">fin</span> <span class=\"n\">p₁</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">X₂</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">matrix</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">fin</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">fin</span> <span class=\"n\">p₂</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Turn into</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">variable</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">rs</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">set</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">fin</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"bp\">→</span> <span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">))</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- So I can do</span>\n<span class=\"k\">#check</span> <span class=\"n\">submodule.span</span> <span class=\"n\">ℝ</span> <span class=\"n\">rs</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 277296130,
        "sender_full_name": "Aron Erben",
        "timestamp": 1648739518
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>matrix m n R</code> is just an abbreviation for <code>m → n → R</code>, so you can use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/set.range\">docs#set.range</a>, the range of a function</p>",
        "id": 277296684,
        "sender_full_name": "Anne Baanen",
        "timestamp": 1648739737
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>More precisely, the columns of a matrix <code>A</code> would be <code>set.range A.transpose</code></p>",
        "id": 277296775,
        "sender_full_name": "Anne Baanen",
        "timestamp": 1648739763
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or written another way, <code>set.range (λ i, (λ j, A j i))</code></p>",
        "id": 277296854,
        "sender_full_name": "Anne Baanen",
        "timestamp": 1648739799
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Perfect, thank you so much, so <code>#check set.range X₁ᵀ ∪ set.range X₂ᵀ</code> should do it, right?</p>\n<p>I was playing with <code>fintype</code> and <code>finset</code>. I was not aware it was this easy to turn a function into a set, kinda makes sense in retrospect though :)</p>",
        "id": 277297222,
        "sender_full_name": "Aron Erben",
        "timestamp": 1648739954
